    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-04-30T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-04-30T08:00:00-05:00" n="76"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d76">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">883.24/170: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-04-30T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 30, 1943—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:09 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>799. Department’s 593, April 29, 4 [<hi rend="italic">5</hi>] p.m. To avoid
                    reopening discussion British Embassy has not again been approached in premises.
                    Embassy originally stated that phrase in question was intended to refer to all
                    supplies required from abroad by National Defense Ministry whether or not they
                    were of a purely military nature. Embassy draft note copy of which forwarded to
                    Department with Legation’s despatch 973 of April 5<note n="8" xml:id="d76fn8"
                        >Not printed.</note> stated that procedure in question should apply to
                    orders “falling within budget of Ministry of National Defense”.</p>
                <p>Since Department Civil Aviation, for example, is part of National Defense
                    Ministry there would appear to be no doubt that any of that Department’s
                    requirements would be subject to proposed procedure.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
